      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Look, I think that Elon Musk is going to close his deal to buy Twitter Inc.=
 by the end of the month. He   has said he will, Twitter (presumably) wants=
 that, he has the money, he will get extremely in trouble with the Delaware=
 Court of Chancery if he does not, he seems to have a renewed enthusiasm fo=
r messing with Twitter, I think it will happen. (Not, ever, investment advi=
ce!) That said lots of people are understandably skeptical, and he changes =
his mind a lot, so I keep reading theories about how he might still wiggle =
out.
Here I want to discuss two of them briefly, not because I think they are gr=
eat theories but because people keep asking me about them. One is that Musk=
 has put a lot of effort recently into  spreading Russian and Chinese propa=
ganda? On Twitter, he has  endorsed most of Vladimir Putin=E2=80=99s war ai=
ms in Ukraine, and in a lunch interview with the Financial Times he  called=
 for China to annex Taiwan. (There is also  a sketchy report, which he has =
denied, that Musk talked to Putin before endorsing his annexation of parts =
of Ukraine.)=C2=A0He is a man with many weird hobbies, but this is a partic=
ularly odd hobby, and as far as I can tell a new=C2=A0one. One possibility =
here is that (as he says) he is worried about the risk of nuclear war and w=
ants to defuse geopolitical tensions by tweeting polls or whatever. Another=
 possibility is that China is a critical market for Tesla Inc., and he is s=
eeking China=E2=80=99s favor.
But the fancier=C2=A0possibility is that he is trying to=C2=A0get American =
government officials worried, so that they will step in to block the Twitte=
r deal. =E2=80=9CWe can=E2=80=99t let Twitter, the =E2=80=98town square=E2=
=80=99 of American political discourse, be owned by a guy who might be a Ch=
inese or Russian agent, so we have to block the deal,=E2=80=9D people think=
 Musk thinks the government=C2=A0will think. By winkingly hinting=C2=A0that=
 he might be doing Vladimir Putin=E2=80=99s bidding, the theory goes, Musk =
will force the US government to block his acquisition of Twitter. Which wou=
ld get him out of it, which is =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps =E2=80=94=C2=A0what h=
e wants.
I don=E2=80=99t really buy this =E2=80=94=C2=A0I don=E2=80=99t think that t=
he US government has much of a mechanism to block the deal at this point, a=
nd I think it would be too controversial for anyone to touch =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it is a=C2=A0funny=C2=A0theory so I am passing it along. On the othe=
r hand, if you don=E2=80=99t believe this theory, and I don=E2=80=99t, then=
 you are left with an alternative theory like =E2=80=9CMusk really does lik=
e spreading Chinese and Russian propaganda, and now he=E2=80=99ll own Twitt=
er,=E2=80=9D and that=E2=80=99s perhaps not ideal.
The other, less funny=C2=A0theory is that Musk will tank his debt financing=
 for the deal by refusing to deliver a solvency certificate. Musk=E2=80=99s=
 obligation to close the deal is conditional on his banks funding their $13=
 billion loan commitment, and their obligation to fund is conditional on =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0well, it=E2=80=99s conditional on=C2=A0very little; there ar=
e almost no excuses for them not to fund, but there is one. There is a cond=
ition in  the commitment letters that requires that, before funding:
Customary legal opinions, customary officer=E2=80=99s closing certificates =
(including incumbency certificates of officers), organizational documents, =
customary evidence of authorization and good standing certificates in juris=
dictions of formation/organization, in each case with respect to the Borrow=
er and the Guarantors (to the extent applicable), customary requests for bo=
rrowing and a solvency certificate (as of the Closing Date after giving eff=
ect to the Transactions and substantially in the form of Annex E-I attached=
 hereto, certified by a senior authorized financial officer of the Borrower=
) shall have been delivered to the Lead Arrangers.
That is, before the banks will lend money to Twitter so that Musk can buy i=
t, they=E2=80=99ll need some paperwork saying things like =E2=80=9CTwitter =
is a real company=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CTwitter wants to borrow this money=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe person who signed the document on Twitter=E2=80=
=99s behalf actually works at Twitter and is authorized to sign that docume=
nt.=E2=80=9D And they will need some paperwork =E2=80=94=C2=A0the solvency =
certificate =E2=80=94=C2=A0saying that:
=09The sum of the liabilities (including contingent liabilities) of the Bor=
rower and its restricted subsidiaries, on a consolidated basis, does not ex=
ceed the present fair saleable value of the present assets of the Borrower =
and its restricted subsidiaries, on a consolidated basis.=09The fair value =
of the property of the Borrower and its restricted subsidiaries, on a conso=
lidated basis, is greater than the total amount of liabilities (including c=
ontingent liabilities) of the Borrower and its restricted subsidiaries, on =
a consolidated basis as such liabilities become absolute and mature.=09The =
capital of the Borrower and its restricted subsidiaries, on a consolidated =
basis, is not unreasonably small in relation to their business as contempla=
ted on the date hereof.=09The Borrower and its restricted subsidiaries, on =
a consolidated basis, have not incurred and do not intend to incur, or beli=
eve that they will incur, debts including current obligations beyond their =
ability to pay such debts as they become due (whether at maturity or otherw=
ise).

Here I am quoting from the =E2=80=9CForm of Solvency Certificate=E2=80=9D i=
n Annex E-1 to the commitment letters; =E2=80=9Cthe Borrower,=E2=80=9D here=
, means Twitter, though Twitter =E2=80=9Cafter giving effect to=E2=80=9D Mu=
sk=E2=80=99s acquisition. It is not entirely clear to me who has to sign th=
is certificate =E2=80=94=C2=A0technically, it=E2=80=99s an officer of=C2=A0=
Twitter=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but people seem to think that Musk can say =E2=
=80=9Cwell, if I take over Twitter, I will appoint myself as chief financia=
l officer, and then I will refuse to sign this certificate, and then the ba=
nks won=E2=80=99t lend, so I can=E2=80=99t take over Twitter.=E2=80=9D That=
 is convoluted but, fine, I guess, I don=E2=80=99t know.
Could he do this? I mean, (1) not investing advice! but (2) no? He agreed =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0last week! =E2=80=94=C2=A0to pay $46 billion for Twitter, so=
 it would be hard for him to argue that it=E2=80=99s not worth more than $1=
3 billion, the amount it will borrow. And while Twitter=C2=A0will have to w=
ork=C2=A0a bit to pay its debt=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CTwitter now fac=
es an annual interest burden of nearly $1.2 billion,=E2=80=9D reports   Blo=
omberg=E2=80=99s Paula Seligson, and =E2=80=9Cmight not become free-cash-fl=
ow positive until 2025=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 it has a lot of cash on its balan=
ce sheet and is unlikely to run out of money to pay interest anytime soon. =
Twitter will have a lot of debt, but it seems hard to argue that it=E2=80=
=99s insolvent.=C2=A0Also, just, Musk=E2=80=99s lawyers told a court last w=
eek that they expected the banks to fund; if he blows that up now he=E2=80=
=99s going to have a lot of explaining to do. I don=E2=80=99t see it, but I=
 pass it along to you because I know nothing and there are still like two w=
eeks left on this thing. Presumably=C2=A0something=C2=A0will happen that su=
rprises me.

