<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The simplest form of market manipulation is:</=
p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Buy a lot of Thing X, pushing its pri=
ce up.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sell it at the new high pri=
ce, for a profit.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This, I frequently <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMTkvbWFya2V0LW1ha2luZy1pcy1oYXJkLWZv=
ci1ob3VzZXM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1=
fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMDEyJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dW=
Zm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf362cb0d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  point out</a>, should not w=
ork. In Step 1, you push up the price of X by buying it; therefore, in Step=
 2, you will push the price down by selling it. There are no free lunches t=
hat are=C2=A0<em>this simple</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a small modification that seems promis=
ing:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Buy a lot of Thing X, pushing its pri=
ce up.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Borrow against your X:=C2=A0</em>If you have 100 million X, and X is no=
w worth $1, then you have $100 million worth of X, and maybe someone will g=
ive you, say, a $50 million margin loan against it.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">Run away with the $50 million.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The reason this seems promising is that you ar=
e not=C2=A0<em>selling=C2=A0</em>X in Step 2, which means you are not pushi=
ng down its price. Still it strikes me as doubtful, in the general case. Yo=
u had to spend a lot of money to (1) accumulate 100 million X and (2) push =
its price up.=C2=A0If X started at $0.01, and ended at $1, and you bought 1=
00 million of it to get it there, then you probably paid an average price o=
f around $0.50. (You bought your first 1 million at $0.01, your next 1 mill=
ion at $0.02, etc.) So you paid about $50 million to push the value of your=
 holdings to $100 million. But you can=E2=80=99t borrow the full $100 milli=
on: At best, you=E2=80=99ll probably get a margin loan of about $50 million=
. So you=E2=80=99ll get back roughly what you put in, or realistically less=
 given various frictional costs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t want to rule this out entirely=
: This might work=C2=A0if (1) you are=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>at manipulati=
ng the price, in the sense that you know how to make the price move without=
 spending too much money, and (2) someone will give you a margin loan at a =
high loan-to-value ratio. This approach is roughly <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjcvYmlsbC1od2FuZy1hcnJlc3QtaW5za=
WRlLXRoZS12aWNpb3VzLWN5Y2xlLW9mLWFyY2hlZ29zLWNvbGxhcHNlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMTIy=
Ml9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV9=
0ZXJtPTIyMTAxMiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB91=
05fd62" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgroun=
d-color: #ccc;">  what Bill Hwang is accused of at Archegos Capital Managem=
ent</a>: He allegedly traded tactically in ways that moved stock prices a l=
ot,=C2=A0and borrowed 90% or more of the value of his positions from his ba=
nks. If he played it perfectly =E2=80=94=C2=A0and there is no evidence that=
 he did =E2=80=94=C2=A0then he could have taken out way more money than he =
put in, leaving his banks with the losses. Overall though this approach see=
ms hard.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you can work with it. Here is a subtler mo=
dification:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Thing X trades at $0.01.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You go to a not-particularly-busy=C2=A0<em>fut=
ures</em> trading platform, open an account=C2=A0and offer 100 million X fu=
tures for $0.01. Futures are generally leveraged products, where you don=E2=
=80=99t have to pay the full amount of the trade upfront. But let=E2=80=99s=
 say you do: You put up=C2=A0$1 million of collateral for this $1-million-n=
otional position.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You walk out of =
the futures trading platform, put on a fake mustache, walk back in, open a =
new account=C2=A0and bid to=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>100 million X futures. Y=
ou put up, say, $1 million of collateral for this position.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The futures platform is not particularly busy, so=
 no one else wants to buy or sell X futures and you end up trading=C2=A0wit=
h yourself. You don=E2=80=99t move the price of X or anything, but your two=
 orders cross and you end up both long and short 100 million X futures =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0in two different accounts =E2=80=94=C2=A0at $0.01.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You go to a regular exchange and start buying =
X in the open market, pushing the price up to $1. Let=E2=80=99s say X is no=
t all that liquid. You buy 10 million X, starting at $0.01 and ending up at=
 $1. Your average cost is about $0.50, so you spend about $5 million.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You have spent a total of $7 million: =
$1 million to get long futures, $1 million to get short futures, $5 million=
 to push up the price of X.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now yo=
u put the fake mustache back on, go back to the futures exchange and say =
=E2=80=9CI see that my long futures position is in-the-money by $99 million=
. I would like to borrow $40 million against my winnings.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The futures exchange looks at the $1 price=
 on the spot market and says, yep, sure enough, you=E2=80=99re up $99 milli=
on. They want to keep some collateral against this position, but they=E2=80=
=99ll give you some back. So they give you the $40 million, and you stuff i=
t in a suitcase and drive off.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Mea=
nwhile they call you on your other phone number =E2=80=94=C2=A0the number y=
ou gave them in Step 2 =E2=80=94=C2=A0to say =E2=80=9Chey your 100 million =
short futures position moved against you by $99 million, could you please s=
end us that money,=E2=80=9D but that call goes straight to voicemail and th=
ey never hear from you again.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Your=
 net profit is $33 million, the $40 million from Step 8 minus the $7 millio=
n from Steps 2, 3 and 5.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This approach is stupid and should not work. I=
t requires:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A pretty illiquid market for the=C2=A0=
underlying Thing X, so that you can push the price around without spending =
much money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A very sleepy futures =
market, where you can just trade with yourself without anyone noticing and =
without moving the price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A future=
s market that will let you trade very large=C2=A0<em>size</em>, despite bei=
ng very sleepy: Given how illiquid and volatile Thing X is in my example, i=
t would be silly for a futures market to actually let you put on a 100 mill=
ion X futures position, particularly with so little collateral.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A futures market that will cheerfully=C2=A0<e=
m>cash you out=C2=A0</em>on your unrealized gains in Step 7, even though th=
e contract has moved in your favor rapidly and suspiciously.=C2=A0</li>=09<=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A futures market that won=E2=80=99t come a=
fter you for your losses in Step 9.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think you would have a hard time running thi=
s trade in, like, the oil market. Still it hangs together in a rough schema=
tic way, which means you can try it in the=C2=A0<em>crypto=C2=A0</em>market=
. Crypto, particularly decentralized finance, has some key advantages for t=
his, including:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Weird and fragmented liquidity, so tha=
t you can trade with yourself on a futures exchange, and you can move the p=
rice of a token a lot on the spot market;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom=
: 5px;">A love of mechanical rules and automated markets, so that if your X=
 position spikes from $1 million to $100 million, some decentralized financ=
e platform will say =E2=80=9Cyup, now it=E2=80=99s worth $100 million, so i=
t=E2=80=99s good collateral for a $40 million loan=E2=80=9D; and</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A presumption of anonymity, so exchanges wil=
l let you trade with yourself, and won=E2=80=99t be able to come after you =
for your losses, since they just have some anonymous wallet addresses.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTIvY3J5cHRvLXBsYXRmb3JtLW1hbmdvLWhpdC1ieS1sYXRlc3QtaGFjay1=
pbi1kaWdpdGFsLWFzc2V0LXNlY3Rvcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDEyMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbW=
VkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEwMTImdXRtX2Nhb=
XBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8ae2eb58" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Here you =
go</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An attacker spirited away about $100 million f=
rom decentralized finance provider Mango by manipulating the price of its t=
oken in an exploit that wiped out depositors on the crypto platform.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The heist began with two accounts funded with =
the stablecoin USD Coin, the platform said Wednesday on Twitter. The accoun=
ts took large positions in Mango perpetual futures, causing the price of th=
e Mango token to spike.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The price jump stoked an unrealized profit fro=
m the futures. The attacker used that to borrow and withdraw roughly a net =
$100 million from the protocol in a range of tokens -- leaving depositors w=
ith nothing, according to Mango.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis incident has effectively resulte=
d in a total draining of all equity available,=E2=80=9D the platform said o=
n Twitter, adding the attackers are communicating with Mango and =E2=80=9Ci=
ndicating a willingness to negotiate.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto derivatives trader Joshua Lim <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6L=
y90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9qb3NodWFfal9saW0vc3RhdHVzLzE1Nzk5ODc2NDg1NDYyNDY2NTg/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cB61411472" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> explained the exploit on Twitter</a=
>, and it is pretty much the schematic thing I laid out above. The attacker=
 funded one account on the Mango perpetual futures exchange with $5 million=
, offered 483 million futures on Mango=E2=80=99s own MNGO governance=C2=A0t=
oken, funded another account with another $5 million, and lifted those 483 =
million futures at a price of $0.0382. Then the =E2=80=9Cattacker started t=
o move the price of MNGO=E2=80=9D on the spot market, by buying MNGO tokens=
 on centralized exchanges. =E2=80=9CAt MNGO/USD price of $0.91 per unit, ac=
count B was in the money by 483mm * ($0.91 - $0.03298) =3D $423mm,=E2=80=9D=
 and =E2=80=9Cthat was enough unrealized P&amp;L to take out a loan of $116=
mm across a bunch of tokens, which then left Mango and leaves the protocol =
at a deficit.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look, I had never heard of the Mango token unt=
il this morning, which is a crucial advantage for me. If you had come to me=
 and said =E2=80=9CI have Mango tokens with a market value of $423 million,=
 I want to use them as collateral for a loan, would you lend me $116 millio=
n against these Mango tokens?=E2=80=9D I would have said =E2=80=9Cabsolutel=
y not, Mango tokens, not a thing.=E2=80=9D And that would have been=C2=A0<e=
m>correct</em>, both in the narrow sense that the =E2=80=9Creal=E2=80=9D ma=
rket value of 483 million Mango tokens was about $18 million and in the bro=
ader sense of, well, why was it even $18 million? But the Mango protocol it=
self just had some price oracles that connected to some exchanges, and when=
 those exchanges showed that the tokens were trading at $0.91, it believed =
them. So it=C2=A0computed a value of $423 million, and that was plenty of c=
ollateral to support a $116 million loan, and there you go.=C2=A0Mango coul=
d look at market prices, but it could not apply common sense, and that was =
its problem.</p>
