<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bored apes</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bored Ape Yacht Club (BAYC) is an entity that =
owns the intellectual property rights to some cartoons and tries to make mo=
ney by <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29351707.29=
2269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDUtMj=
UvdGVycmEtaXMtYmFjay1mcm9tLWJhbmtydXB0Y3k_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVR=
kYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMDEy=
JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB793bb47f" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>
licensing them to Seth Green or whatever</a>. BAYC issues several sorts of =
financial instruments, including =E2=80=9CApes,=E2=80=9D which convey certa=
in intellectual property rights to particular cartoons, and =E2=80=9CApeCoi=
ns,=E2=80=9D which give you the right to vote on things like (1) who BAYC s=
hould license its cartoons to and (2) how the money should be spent. These =
instruments trade on financial markets, and the more demand there is for=C2=
=A0the cartoons=C2=A0(and the more money BAYC makes), the more valuable Ape=
s and ApeCoins will=C2=A0be.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is a loose description of the situation, =
and you could=C2=A0quibble with some details. Still I think it is more righ=
t than wrong. What legal conclusions can you draw from it? It=E2=80=99s nev=
er legal advice around here, but here are some thoughts:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">ApeCoins are=C2=A0<em>shares of stock=
=C2=A0</em>in the BAYC entity, and are therefore securities under US law;</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Apes are=C2=A0<em>arguably=C2=A0</e=
m>securities under US law, though it is debatable.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9jb3JwZmluL2ZyYW1ld2=
9yay1pbnZlc3RtZW50LWNvbnRyYWN0LWFuYWx5c2lzLWRpZ2l0YWwtYXNzZXRz/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB2d988943" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;">security is</a> =E2=80=9Cthe investment of m=
oney in a common enterprise with a reasonable expectation of profits to be =
derived from the efforts of others.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Is an Ape =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
which conveys certain rights to one particular cartoon =E2=80=94=C2=A0an in=
vestment in the =E2=80=9Ccommon enterprise=E2=80=9D of BAYC, or is it more =
like buying a particular work of art that you can then do with as you pleas=
e? I think there=E2=80=99s a pretty good case that it=E2=80=99s more like a=
 work of art, like buying a cartoon =E2=80=94=C2=A0even though the value of=
 that cartoon will obviously depend on the collective value of BAYC and the=
 efforts of its managers. But the ApeCoins =E2=80=94=C2=A0which are fungibl=
e and carry voting rights to do things like <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcGVjb2luLmNvbS9nb3Zlc=
m5hbmNlI2dlbmVyYWwtZ3VpZGVsaW5lcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfc27f2bf" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> elect the board of directors</a> of BAYC =E2=80=94=C2=A0I mean, what cou=
ld they possibly be but securities of the entity that is BAYC?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGlj=
bGVzLzIwMjItMTAtMTEvYm9yZWQtYXBlLWNyZWF0b3IteXVnYS1sYWJzLWZhY2VzLXNlYy1wcm9=
iZS1vdmVyLXVucmVnaXN0ZXJlZC1vZmZlcmluZ3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTAxMjIyX01PTkVZU1RVRk=
YmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIxMDEyJ=
nV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2e5eacde" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 Anyway</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The US Securities and Exchange Commission is i=
nvestigating Yuga Labs Inc., the creator of the popular Bored Ape Yacht Clu=
b collection of NFTs, over whether sales of its digital assets violate fede=
ral law.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC is examining whether certain nonfungib=
le tokens from the Miami-based company are more akin to stocks and should f=
ollow the same disclosure rules, according to a person familiar with the ma=
tter, who asked not to be named because the probe is private. Wall Street=
=E2=80=99s main regulator is also examining the distribution of ApeCoin, wh=
ich was given to holders of Bored Ape Yacht Club and related NFTs. The cryp=
tocurrency was created in part for web3, a vision of a decentralized intern=
et built around blockchains.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now I think that BAYC has some good defenses=
=C2=A0here. =E2=80=9CCertain nonfungible tokens=C2=A0from the Miami-based c=
ompany=E2=80=9D (Apes, and various spinoff cartoons)=C2=A0<em>may=C2=A0</em=
>in fact be =E2=80=9Cmore akin to stocks,=E2=80=9D but I think there=E2=80=
=99s a good argument that they=E2=80=99re not. (They=E2=80=99re works of ar=
t, let=E2=80=99s say.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile=C2=A0ApeCoin seems like stock to me,=
 but for the most part Yuga/BAYC did not=C2=A0<em>sell it for cash: </em>Ap=
eCoins were=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
9351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly9hcGVjb2luLmNvbS9hYm91dA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB=
40847b88" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgro=
und-color: #ccc;">given away to holders of Apes</a>, without payment, so th=
ere was no investment of money and no offering for cash. Meanwhile hundreds=
 of millions=C2=A0more ApeCoins were given to the BAYC treasury (to be sold=
 to raise cash for the entity), to Yuga Labs (to reward the corporation for=
 its investment in building=C2=A0BAYC) and to its founders and=C2=A0other =
=E2=80=9Claunch contributors,=E2=80=9D all of which can be sold for cash, b=
ut most (not all) of those were locked up for 12 months or more, so Yuga an=
d BAYC have an argument that they did not do an illegal securities offering=
.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: tran=
sparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0=E2=80=9CSure we gave out stock, but we didn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>s=
ell=C2=A0</em>it, so it=E2=80=99s fine,=E2=80=9D is roughly the defense, wh=
ich is not perfect but also not ridiculous.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still I guess the main points here are=C2=A0(1=
) governance tokens of=C2=A0crypto projects are probably securities and (2)=
 the SEC has noticed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One other thing. I have called BAYC an =E2=80=
=9Centity,=E2=80=9D which is a nice generic term, but it appears to <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6L=
y9hcGVjb2luLmNvbS9nb3Zlcm5hbmNl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBad16e026" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 call itself a DAO</a>, a decentralized autonomous organization. There are =
some advantages to calling your entity a DAO rather than a corporation. For=
 one thing, shares of stock of corporations are=C2=A0<em>obviously=C2=A0</e=
m>securities subject to SEC regulation, while governance tokens of DAOs are=
 =E2=80=A6=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>obviously securities subject to SEC regu=
lation, I think, and the SEC thinks, but some people seem to disagree. So y=
ou can say =E2=80=9Cwhat, it=E2=80=99s a DAO, governance tokens, not stock,=
 no securities here,=E2=80=9D and maybe someone will believe you. For anoth=
er thing, it is good marketing: The people buying your DAO governance token=
s believe in a future of crypto and decentralization, and they=E2=80=99d be=
 disappointed to buy shares of stock in a corporation. They want some =E2=
=80=9Cdecentralization=E2=80=9D branding on their shares, so you give it to=
 them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is also a big disadvantage to callin=
g your entity a DAO rather than a corporation. A corporation is a particula=
r sort of legal entity that has one key feature, which is=C2=A0<em>limited =
liability</em>. If you own shares of a corporation, you are not generally r=
esponsible for (1) the debts of that corporation or (2) its crimes. (If you=
 are also an executive and you=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>the crimes, you are re=
sponsible, but=C2=A0<em>simply being a shareholder=C2=A0</em>does not make =
you responsible for the actions of the corporation.) This is a special feat=
ure of corporations (and some other entities like limited liability compani=
es or limited partnerships), and corporations have to take affirmative step=
s (file incorporation documents, pay fees, etc.) to get this protection.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you don=E2=80=99t do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0if=
 you just get together with your buddies and start a business without incor=
porating it =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you don=E2=80=99t get those protections. In=
stead, you have the default form of business organization, just a group of =
people doing a business without paperwork, which might be=C2=A0called a =E2=
=80=9Cgeneral partnership=E2=80=9D or an =E2=80=9Cunincorporated associatio=
n.=E2=80=9D A general partnership <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudXNjaGFtYmVyLmNvbS9jby9zdGF=
ydC9zdGFydHVwL2dlbmVyYWwtcGFydG5lcnNoaXBz/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3461f887=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> does=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>have limited liability</a>. If your =
partnership incurs a debt =E2=80=94 if one of your partners borrows money o=
n behalf of the partnership and then loses it =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you are r=
esponsible for it. If the partnership does crimes, you might get in trouble=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is why people, in traditional business, t=
end to do the paperwork to form corporations (or=C2=A0limited liability com=
panies, limited partnerships, etc.). In crypto business, some combination o=
f libertarianism, naivety, we=E2=80=99re-doing-stuff-no-one-has-seen-before=
 exceptionalism, and a desire to evade securities laws leads people to=C2=
=A0<em>avoid=C2=A0</em>that paperwork. And then you have a DAO with no pape=
rwork, which is a general partnership, and oops.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so last month the US Commodity Futures Tra=
ding Commission <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29=
351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1ByZXNzUmVsZWFzZXMvO=
DU5MC0yMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB734891bd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> brought an enforcemen=
t action</a> against a decentralized finance platform called bZeroX and a D=
AO called Ooki DAO, and said:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Ooki DAO is an unincorporated =
association comprised of holders of OokiDAO Tokens (=E2=80=9COoki Tokens=E2=
=80=9D) who vote those tokens to govern (e.g., to modify, operate, market, =
and take other actions with respect to) the bZx Protocol (which the Ooki DA=
O has renamed the =E2=80=9COoki Protocol=E2=80=9D).=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The CFTC=E2=80=99s view is that just<em> buyin=
g</em> governance tokens doesn=E2=80=99t make you a general partner in the =
DAO, but buying those tokens and <em>voting</em> them does. As one CFTC com=
missioner <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29351707=
.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Z0Yy5nb3YvUHJlc3NSb29tL1NwZWVjaGVzVGVzdGltb255L21=
lcnNpbmdlcnN0YXRlbWVudDA5MjIyMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfc5affef" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 said in dissent</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Under the Commission=E2=80=99s def=
inition, [a token holder who votes] has now become a member of the unincorp=
orated association and (possibly unknowingly) assumed personal liability an=
d is subject to CFTC sanctions for any violations of the [Commodity Exchang=
e Act]=C2=A0by the Ooki DAO.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is possible that DAOs are just the worst of=
 all worlds: Their tokens are similar enough to corporate shares to be subj=
ect to securities laws, but different enough to create unlimited liability =
for their holders.</p>
