scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">block his acquisition of Twitter=
</a>. Which would get him out of it, which is =E2=80=94=C2=A0perhaps =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0what he wants.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t really buy this =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0I don=E2=80=99t think that the US government has much of a mechanism to =
block the deal at this point, and I think it would be too controversial for=
 anyone to touch =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is a=C2=A0<em>funny=C2=A0</em>theory=
 so I am passing it along. On the other hand, if you don=E2=80=99t believe =
this theory, and I don=E2=80=99t, then you are left with an alternative the=
ory like =E2=80=9CMusk really does like spreading Chinese and Russian propa=
ganda, and now he=E2=80=99ll own Twitter,=E2=80=9D and that=E2=80=99s perha=
ps not ideal.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other, less funny=C2=A0theory is that Musk=
 will tank his debt financing for the deal by refusing to deliver a solvenc=
y certificate. Musk=E2=80=99s obligation to close the deal is conditional o=
n his banks funding their $13 billion loan commitment, and their obligation=
 to fund is conditional on =E2=80=94=C2=A0well, it=E2=80=99s conditional on=
=C2=A0<em>very little</em>; there are almost no excuses for them not to fun=
d, but there is one. There is a condition in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNo=
aXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTgwOTEvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMDQ5ODQ0L3RtMjIxMzE4OWQ4X2V=
4OTktaC5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17ac541e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the commitment let=
ters</a> that requires that, before funding:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Customary legal opinions, customar=
y officer=E2=80=99s closing certificates (including incumbency certificates=
 of officers), organizational documents, customary evidence of authorizatio=
n and good standing certificates in jurisdictions of formation/organization=
, in each case with respect to the Borrower and the Guarantors (to the exte=
nt applicable), customary requests for borrowing and a solvency certificate=
 (as of the Closing Date after giving effect to the Transactions and substa=
ntially in the form of Annex E-I attached hereto, certified by a senior aut=
horized financial officer of the Borrower) shall have been delivered to the=
 Lead Arrangers.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, before the banks will lend money to T=
witter so that Musk can buy it, they=E2=80=99ll need some paperwork saying =
things like =E2=80=9CTwitter is a real company=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CTwitte=
r wants to borrow this money=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthe person who signed th=
e document on Twitter=E2=80=99s behalf actually works at Twitter and is aut=
horized to sign that document.=E2=80=9D And they will need some paperwork =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0the solvency certificate =E2=80=94=C2=A0saying that:</p>
<blockquote><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; marg=
in: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The sum of the liabilitie=
s (including contingent liabilities) of the Borrower and its restricted sub=
sidiaries, on a consolidated basis, does not exceed the present fair saleab=
le value of the present assets of the Borrower and its restricted subsidiar=
ies, on a consolidated basis.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The =
fair value of the property of the Borrower and its restricted subsidiaries,=
 on a consolidated basis, is greater than the total amount of liabilities (=
including contingent liabilities) of the Borrower and its restricted subsid=
iaries, on a consolidated basis as such liabilities become absolute and mat=
ure.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The capital of the Borrower a=
nd its restricted subsidiaries, on a consolidated basis, is not unreasonabl=
y small in relation to their business as contemplated on the date hereof.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The Borrower and its restricted sub=
sidiaries, on a consolidated basis, have not incurred and do not intend to =
incur, or believe that they will incur, debts including current obligations=
 beyond their ability to pay such debts as they become due (whether at matu=
rity or otherwise).</li>
</ol></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here I am quoting from the =E2=80=9CForm of So=
lvency Certificate=E2=80=9D in Annex E-1 to the commitment letters; =E2=80=
=9Cthe Borrower,=E2=80=9D here, means Twitter, though Twitter =E2=80=9Cafte=
r giving effect to=E2=80=9D Musk=E2=80=99s acquisition. It is not entirely =
clear to me who has to sign this certificate =E2=80=94=C2=A0technically, it=
=E2=80=99s an officer of=C2=A0<em>Twitter=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0but peop=
le seem to think that Musk can say =E2=80=9Cwell, if I take over Twitter, I=
 will appoint myself as chief financial officer, and then I will refuse to =
sign this certificate, and then the banks won=E2=80=99t lend, so I can=E2=
=80=99t take over Twitter.=E2=80=9D That is convoluted but, fine, I guess, =
I don=E2=80=99t know.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Could he do this? I mean, (1) not investing ad=
vice! but (2) no? He agreed =E2=80=94=C2=A0<em>last week! =E2=80=94=C2=A0</=
em>to pay $46 billion for Twitter, so it would be hard for him to argue tha=
t it=E2=80=99s not worth more than $13 billion, the amount it will borrow. =
And while Twitter=C2=A0<em>will</em> have to work=C2=A0a bit to pay its deb=
t=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9CTwitter now faces an annual interest burden =
of nearly $1.2 billion,=E2=80=9D reports <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/29351707.292269/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9u=
